'''Charles Edward (Chuck) Hinton, Jr.''' (born May 3, 1934 in [[Rocky Mount, North Carolina]]) is a former [[utility player|utility]] in [[Major League Baseball]] who played for the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Washington Senators]] (1961-64), [[Cleveland Indians]] (1965-67, 1969-71) and [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim|California Angels]] (1968). He batted and threw right-handed.

In an eleven-season career, Hinton posted a .264 [[batting average]] with 113 [[home run]]s and 443 [[run batted in|RBI]] in 1353 [[games played]]. 

==Best Season==
*{{By|1962}}: .310 BA, 75 RBI, 80 [[run (baseball)|runs]], 168 [[hit (baseball)|hits]], 25 [[double (baseball)|doubles]], 28 [[stolen base]]s, 151 games <U+2013> all career-highs

==Highlights==
*[[MLB All-Star Game|1964 American League All-Star]]
*Two [[hitting streak|hitting-streaks]] in 1962 (17 and 15 games)
*Fourth in the 1962 American League batting title (.310), behind [[Pete Runnels]] (.326), [[Mickey Mantle]] (.321) and [[Floyd Robinson]] (.312)
*Three times led the Washington Senators in batting average (1962-64), four times in [[triple (baseball)|triples]] and stolen bases (1961-64), and was the last Senator to hit .300 
*His uniform number 32 is honored in the [[Washington Nationals|Washington Wall of Stars]]

